"},{"camp":"Holzminden internment camp","from_date":"1917-11-02"},{"camp":"Holland (neutral internment via Anglo-German exchange)","from_date":"1918-03-18"},{"camp":"Prince of Wales Hospital, London (admitted for gas poisoning effects)","from_date":"1918-11-02"}],"duration_years":"3.5 (April 1915 - March 1918 in German camps; March-November 1918 Holland internment + UK hospital)"},"awards":[{"award":"Mentioned in Despatches, 'A' List","award_date":"1920-01-30","source":"London Gazette Issue 31759","citation":"The names of the undermentioned Officers, Warrant Officers, Non-Commissioned Officers and Men have been brought to the notice of the Secretary of State for War, in accordance with the terms of Army Order 193 of 1919, for gallant conduct and determination displayed in escaping or attempting to escape from captivity. Dated 5th May, 1919."}],"notes":"Reported missing April 28, 1915 — captured by enemy at Staden Belgium during Second Battle of Ypres (when German forces first deployed chlorine gas on Western Front). GSW 3rd finger left hand at capture. POW journey through seven German camps over 3.5 years: Reserve Lazarett Hofgeismar (field hospital, Jun 1915) → Munden (Jul 1915) → Wesel (Nov 1916) → Crefeld (May 1917) → Schwarmstedt (Jul 1917) → Holzminden (Nov 1917). Transferred to neutral Holland for internment via Anglo-German prisoner exchange Mar 18, 1918. Arrived Prince of Wales Hospital London Nov 2, 1918 admitted for effects of gas poisoning. Died of influenza pneumonia Nov 23, 1918 — 12 days post-Armistice — age 26. Buried Family Plot L 8 Range 24 St Jude's Cemetery Oakville. Commemorated at Oakville War Memorial. Mentioned in Despatches 'A' List awarded Jan 30, 1920 (London Gazette Issue 31759) for gallant conduct and determination in escape attempts. Service file B0507-S008 available at LAC. CWGC ID 425227."}],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["wwi","pandemic_death","canada_migration","pow","mentioned_in_despatches","mortgage_broker","second_ypres","gas_poisoning"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Captured Second Ypres 1915, three camps later","body":"Captain Edward Osler 'Tod' Bath embarked for France April 1, 1915 with the 15th Battalion Canadian Infantry. He was reported missing April 28, 1915 — captured at Staden Belgium during the Second Battle of Ypres, the same campaign in which German forces first deployed chlorine gas on the Western Front. He arrived at his first German camp with a gunshot wound to the third finger of his left hand."},{"number":2,"category":"honors","header":"Mentioned in Despatches for escape attempts","body":"After Tod Bath's death the British government Mentioned him in Despatches on the 'A' List — published in the London Gazette Issue 31759, January 30, 1920 — for gallant conduct and determination displayed in escaping or attempting to escape from captivity during his three years in German custody. The award placed him among the small group of Canadian officers formally recognized for escape activity in WWI prisoner camps."},{"number":3,"category":"death","header":"Gas poisoning and flu killed him post-Armistice","body":"Released to Holland for internment March 18, 1918 and repatriated to England aboard a hospital ship arriving November 2, 1918, he was admitted to Prince of Wales Hospital London for the effects of gas poisoning. He died of influenza and pneumonia at Endsleigh Palace Hospital London on November 23, 1918 — twelve days after the Armistice — at age 26. He was buried in his family plot at St Jude's Cemetery Oakville and is commemorated on the Oakville War Memorial."}],"quotes":[{"text":"for gallant conduct and determination displayed in escaping or attempting to escape from captivity","source":"London Gazette Issue 31759, January 30, 1920 — Mentioned in Despatches 'A' List citation","date":"1920-01-30","notes":"The official citation for Tod Bath's posthumous Mentioned in Despatches award."}],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave #107442815","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/107442815/edward_osler-bath"},{"label":"Canadian Great War Project — Edward Osler Bath","url":"https://canadiangreatwarproject.com/search.php?fname=Edward+Osler&sname=Bath"},{"label":"CWGC casualty record","url":"https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/425227/"},{"label":"LAC personnel record","url":"https://recherche-collection-search.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/Home/Record?app=pffww&IdNumber=29046"},{"label":"Veterans Affairs Canada Virtual War Memorial","url":"https://www.veterans.gc.ca/eng/remembrance/memorials/canadian-virtual-war-memorial/detail/425227"},{"label":"Service file B0507-S008 (LAC download)","url":"https://central.bac-lac.gc.ca/.item/?op=pdf&app=CEF&id=B0507-S008"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[{"type":"Military service file","name":"B0507-S008 CEF Personnel File","url":"https://central.bac-lac.gc.ca/.item/?op=pdf&app=CEF&id=B0507-S008","notes":"Canadian Expeditionary Force personnel service file, digitized by Library and Archives Canada."}],"slug":"edward-bath-1892"},"HD4227":{"id":"HD4227","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Gwendolyn","middle_name":"Margaret","last_name":"Wilson","maiden_name":"Bath","married_names":["Wilson"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Gwendolyn Margaret Bath Wilson"},"birth":{"year":1895,"month":11,"day":7,"state":"Ontario","country":"Canada"},"baptism":{},"death":{},"residence":{},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":10,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"I00644","mother_id":"HD4215"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["canada_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"gwendolyn-wilson-1895"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM336","name":"St Jude's Cemetery","city":"Oakville","state":"Ontario","country":"Canada","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2132382/st-jude's-cemetery","hooker_connections":["HD4215","HD4225","HD4226","I00644","I00651"],"notes":"St Jude's Cemetery, Oakville Halton Regional Municipality Ontario. Burial site of the Bath family — Alice Ruth Whitney Bath (Hooker descendant) and her husband Percy Atkinson Bath, along with their children including WWI POW Capt. Edward Osler 'Tod' Bath."},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}